\begin_layout Subsection
Equilibrium Requirements
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that the equilibrium concept we want to apply is SPNE (or trivially
 PBE).
 If we backward induct, we can figure out how consumers maximize their expected
 utility by choosing the intended contract.
 Recall the two conditions from lecture:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Participation Constraint/Individual Rationality Constraint
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This means that the consumer will receive more than his or her reservation
 value (payoff if she does nothing, or in this case, not buy insurance).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $(IR_{G}):$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{G}(\vec{s}_{G})\geq U_{G}(no\, insurance)\Rightarrow p_{G}\cdot u(s_{2G})+(1-p_{G})\cdot u(s_{1G})\geq p_{G}\cdot u(W-L)+(1-p_{G})\cdot u(W)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $(IR_{B}):$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{B}(\vec{s}_{B})\geq U_{B}(no\, insurance)\Rightarrow p_{B}\cdot u(s_{2B})+(1-p_{B})\cdot u(s_{1B})\geq p_{B}\cdot u(W-L)+(1-p_{B})\cdot u(W)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Incentive Compatibility Constraints
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This means that each type of consumer will prefer the contract intended
 for her type than any other contract intended for another type of consumer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $(IC_{G}):$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{G}(\vec{s}_{G})\geq U_{G}(\vec{s}_{B})\Rightarrow p_{G}\cdot u(s_{2G})+(1-p_{G})\cdot u(s_{1G})\geq p_{G}\cdot u(s_{2B})+(1-p_{G})\cdot u(s_{1B})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $(IC_{B}):$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{B}(\vec{s}_{B})\geq U_{B}(\vec{s}_{G})\Rightarrow p_{B}\cdot u(s_{2B})+(1-p_{B})\cdot u(s_{1B})\geq p_{B}\cdot u(s_{2G})+(1-p_{B})\cdot u(s_{1G})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Give these four constraints, the insurer will choose its optimal policy.
 Try to understand why the IC and IR constraints bind with equality in some
 instances and remain slack in other instances.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Full Information (First-Degree Price Discrimination)
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Full-Information-(First-Degree"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the firm is able to observe whether the consumer is a good type or
 a bad type, the insurer is able to provide insurance such that it will
 maximize its profit conditioning on the probabilities of loss.
 The result is that the entire surplus generated by this trade will go to
 the insurer.
 Note that the IC constraints are not necessary when we have full information.
 The insurer solves the following problem for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
\max_{s_{1i},s_{2i}}\left\{ W-p_{i}L-\left[p_{i}s_{2i}+(1-p_{i})s_{1i}\right]\right\} \]

\end_inset

subject to the Individual Rationality constraint of each 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
(IR_{i}):\, p_{i}\cdot u(s_{2i})+(1-p_{i})\cdot u(s_{1i})\geq p_{i}\cdot u(W-L)+(1-p_{i})\cdot u(W)\]

\end_inset

which will bind with equality or else the insurer can always reduce its
 payout (R) in State 2 (which makes the insurer better off) without violating
 the IR constraint.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where have we seen a similar optimization problem? Think back to the UMPs,
 CMPs, and PMPs from Econ 2020a.
 The solution to the optimization problem should be fairly easy once you
 realize the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Do you see that you have a linear objective function in the choice variables?
 If you don't see this, check out equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "linear iso profit"

\end_inset

 above.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The IR constraint can be written as:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \[
p_{i}\cdot u(s_{2i})+(1-p_{i})\cdot u(s_{1i})\geq\underbar{u}\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\underbar{u}$
\end_inset

 is a constant since 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

 are exogenous parameters to the model.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
In short, we have an optimization problem where the optimum will be at the
 point where the objective function will be tangent to the convex constraint
 set.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Convexity of the constraint set is implied by the assumptions we placed
 on the Bernoulli utility functions.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 There are several ways to solve this problem, but the easiest seems to
 be that at the optimum 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[s_{1i}^{*},s_{2i}^{*}\right]$
\end_inset

 the following must hold:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
-\frac{\left(1-p_{i}\right)}{p_{i}} & = & \frac{\partial s_{2i}}{\partial s_{1i}}\Rightarrow-\frac{\left(1-p_{i}\right)}{p_{i}}=-\frac{(1-p_{i})u'(s_{1i})}{p_{i}u'(s_{2i})}\Rightarrow u'(s_{1i})=u'(s_{2i})\nonumber \\
 & \therefore & s_{1i}=s_{2i}\label{optimization solution}\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The important thing to understand here is that we are at a Pareto Optimum
 (or the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

First Best
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) when we have full information and First Degree Price Discrimination.
 Further, because the IR constraint binds at the optimum contract, the insurer
 gets all of the surplus and the consumer gets her reservation utility.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Asymmetric Information (Second-Degree Price Discrimination)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Optimization Problem of the Insurer
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the insurer is unable to distinguish between the different types of consumers
, then its problem can be written as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
\max_{s_{1G},s_{2G},s_{1B},s_{2B}}\lambda\left\{ W-p_{G}L-\left[p_{G}s_{2G}+(1-p_{G})s_{1G}\right]\right\} +(1-\lambda)\left\{ W-p_{B}L-\left[p_{B}s_{2B}+(1-p_{B})s_{1B}\right]\right\} \]

\end_inset

subject to the IR constraints for both consumer types and the IC constraints
 for both consumer types:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $(IR_{G}):$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{G}\cdot u(s_{2G})+(1-p_{G})\cdot u(s_{1G})\geq p_{G}\cdot u(W-L)+(1-p_{G})\cdot u(W)=\bar{u}_{0}^{G}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $(IR_{B}):$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{B}\cdot u(s_{2B})+(1-p_{B})\cdot u(s_{1B})\geq p_{B}\cdot u(W-L)+(1-p_{B})\cdot u(W)=\bar{u}_{0}^{B}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $(IC_{G}):$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{G}\cdot u(s_{2G})+(1-p_{G})\cdot u(s_{1G})\geq p_{G}\cdot u(s_{2B})+(1-p_{G})\cdot u(s_{1B})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $(IC_{B}):$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{B}\cdot u(s_{2B})+(1-p_{B})\cdot u(s_{1B})\geq p_{B}\cdot u(s_{2G})+(1-p_{B})\cdot u(s_{1G})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Results: Binding Constraints
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now let's look at some qualitative results of the optimization problem facing
 the insurer.
 Which of the constraints above bind with equality? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Consider the following:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
p_{B}\cdot u(s_{2B})+(1-p_{B})\cdot u(s_{1B}) & \geq & p_{B}\cdot u(s_{2G})+(1-p_{B})\cdot u(s_{1G})\\
 & > & p_{G}\cdot u(s_{2G})+(1-p_{G})\cdot u(s_{1G})\\
 & \geq & p_{G}\cdot u(W-L)+(1-p_{G})\cdot u(W)\\
 & > & p_{B}\cdot u(W-L)+(1-p_{B})\cdot u(W)\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

The first weak inequality comes from 
\begin_inset Formula $IC_{B}$
\end_inset

; the second strict inequality comes from the single crossing property;
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Understanding this can be a little bit tricky, but try totally differentiating
 the expected utility functions 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{G}(no\, insurance)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{B}(no\, insurance)$
\end_inset

.
 You'll notice that 
\begin_inset Formula $dU_{B}>dU_{G}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 the third weak inequality comes from the 
\begin_inset Formula $IR_{G}$
\end_inset

; and the fourth inequality is because 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{B}>p_{G}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, we have that:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \[
p_{B}\cdot u(s_{2B})+(1-p_{B})\cdot u(s_{1B})>p_{B}\cdot u(W-L)+(1-p_{B})\cdot u(W)\]

\end_inset

which means that the 
\begin_inset Formula $IR_{B}$
\end_inset

 is slack and does not bind.
 This is interpreted as 
\shape italic
the high risk consumers (or bad types) receive a rent
\shape default
.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See Appendix A-2.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Let's look at the 
\begin_inset Formula $IR_{G}$
\end_inset

.
 If the Individual Rationality constraint for the good types (or low risk
 consumers) is slack, this means that both Individual Rationality constraints
 (for the Good and the Bad type) are slack.
 The insurer can reduce payments to both good and bad types in the state
 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{2}$
\end_inset

 without violating either of their Individual Rationality constraints---
\shape italic
i.e.

\shape default
 there is a profitable deviation for the insurer.
 Therefore, it must be the case that 
\begin_inset Formula $IR_{G}$
\end_inset

 binds with equality:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \[
p_{G}\cdot u(s_{2G})+(1-p_{G})\cdot u(s_{1G})=p_{G}\cdot u(W-L)+(1-p_{G})\cdot u(W)\]

\end_inset

which is interpreted as the 
\shape italic
low risk, good types of consumers do not receive a rent above their Individual
 Rationality constraint
\shape default
.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See Appendix A-3.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
It must also be the case that 
\begin_inset Formula $IC_{B}$
\end_inset

 binds with equality because if it was slack, then the insurer could always
 increase its profit by increasing the premium to bad type consumers.
 Furthermore, 
\begin_inset Formula $IC_{G}$
\end_inset

 must be slack.
 If the 
\begin_inset Formula $IC_{G}$
\end_inset

 was binding with equality, then the insurer could again increase its profits
 by increasing the premium charged to the bad types.
 The interpretation of this is that 
\shape italic
the high risk, bad type consumers are indifferent between the contracts
 offered by the insurer.
\shape default

